defaultQ10default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMr McCann:default There has been a large reduction in budget support
default. 
defaultIs that large reduction down to the fact that 
defaultMinister
defaults in the Department have lost faith in providing aid in this way?
defaultMark defaultLowcockdefault: Thank you, Mr McCann
default. 
defaultMaybe I could start and ask Joy to come in
default. 
defaultWhen budget support was introduced about 15 years ago, in its modern variant anyway—budget support was part of the Department’s 
defaultand the Department’s 
defaultpredecessor
defaults’
default programme going back to the 1940s and 1950s—there were essentially four objectives that 
defaultMinister
defaults had
default. 
defaultThe first was to support macro
default-
defaulteconomic stability at a time when lots of countries were coming out of a period of high inflation, with lots of pressure on the external accounts, and some resources to help deal with that big problem was one objective
default. 
defaultThe second was to support recurrent cost financing, essentially paying teachers and health workers for the core essential work that needed to be done to meet the MDGs in countries that were not able to raise enough of their own tax to do that
default.
defaultThe third was to provide an incentive and a means of supporting public financial management reform and public expenditure
default reform
default. 
defaultThe fourth was to make as rational as possible the system by which all of the donors support an individual country, against a background where, as a lot of you have seen, too many finance 
defaultMinister
defaults in the poorest countries spend too much of their time having to talk individually to donors about little things, rather than running their country
default. 
defaultThose were the four objectives 15 years ago
default.
defaultWhat has happened is there has been a lot of progress in the 17 or 18 countries where we were doing especially general budget support on those objectives
default. 
defaultThe core reason why we do less of it now is 
defaultthat 
defaultcountries have progressed
default. 
defaultThat is a good thing
default. 
defaultThere are some short
default&#x2011;
defaultterm things going on as well and events we had to respond to, and Joy can talk a bit about some of that.
defaultJoy defaultHutcheondefault: When I look across the country portfolio, there are two sets of countries
default. 
defaultThere is one where we have a conscious plan to reduce budget support, for the reasons that Mark has talked about
default. 
defaultThat is in countries like 
defaultGhana
default, 
defaultZambia
default and 
defaultMozambique
default. 
defaultAs the Committee will be aware, there are three countries at the moment where we have had to effectively suspend budget support, and those are Rwanda, Uganda—which actually is also in the first category a little—and Malawi
default. 
defaultThere are some different pressures going on
default. 
defaultIn those countries, there is a mixture of reasons, but the fiduciary environment and simply the unacceptable level of risk about putting money as budget support into that fiduciary environment is particularly important in 
defaultMalawi
default and in 
defaultUganda
default.
defaultOne thing we are seeing, and I think we are going to see more of, is an increase in what we call financial aid, which is money that goes through 
defaultGovernment
default systems but is not budget support
default. 
defaultWe are working with a 
defaultGovernment
default, because the 
defaultGovernment
default systems are working and are an effective way of addressing a particular issue, but we are doing it very specifically to achieve a particular set of results or a particular change
default. 
defaultThe fact that budget support is reducing does not mean, per se, that we are stopping supporting 
defaultGovernment
defaults and using 
defaultGovernment
default systems, but we are finding new ways of doing it.
default&#xa0;
