defaultQ13default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFiona O’Donnell:default What assessment have you made of the impact of that reduction in budget support, particularly perhaps on health systems?
defaultMark defaultLowcockdefault: We did a major independent evaluation about four or five years ago now on the impact of budget support
default. 
defaultIt is a really good point
default. 
defaultI do not think we have done a major exercise like that since then
default—
defaultmaybe we should do that
default. 
defaultOne thing we are very careful to do is to try to be aware of the impact of what we do on what others might do
default. 
defaultUnfortunately, there is a bit of a herd effect in international development that, particularly in respect of the 
defaultUK
default, people tend to copy a lot of what the 
defaultUK
default does
default. 
defaultWe are alert to the danger that, if we take a different position in a particular country, others might do that and that could then be detrimental beyond the narrow impact that we make.
defaultAlso, one of the things I mentioned in terms of when countries need budget support less is when they have made progress on increasing their domestic revenue
default. 
defaultOf course, we want to see domestic resources being put to work on the MDGs
default. 
defaultPart of the ongoing dialogue is, when we are providing budget support, never mind when we are graduating from it, can you, a country, invest a bit more of your own resources in paying your health workers and teachers, so that they are on that journey
default. 
defaultHopefully, there is public demand in the country for that to be an important use of tax resources as well
default. 
defaultWe are alert to the danger of reverses of progress
default. 
defaultWe have not seen that in countries in a significant way, but we are alert to the danger of it.
defaultJoy defaultHutcheondefault: To the extent you are asking about when we stop budget support more suddenly because there is a crisis, it is always our first preoccupation to understand how we can continue to support the poor in that country by finding other routes that are acceptable in fiduciary terms.
defaultFiona O’Donnell:default In crisis and non
default&#x2011;
defaultcrisis
default situations, we need to evaluate that and understand what the impact is.
default              
defaultMark defaultLowcockdefault:
default Yes.
